[{"id":32197,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02bTAshMoyZWJ8t6mT2BnX-qnFxBIhfOsqBBRfNWU2g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32323,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mn>11</mn></math>","<math><mn>25</mn></math>","<math><mn>50</mn></math>","<math><mn>15</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"For <math> <mtext>n=5</mtext> </math>&nbsp; <math> <mtext>5s,</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>5p,</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>5d,</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>5f</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext> </math> and <math> <mn>5</mn><mtext>g</mtext> </math> and subshell is available<br /><br />In &nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mtext>s</mtext><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>1</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>orbital</mtext></math><br /><br /><math> <mn>5</mn><mtext>p</mtext><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>3</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>orbital</mtext> </math><br /><br /><math> <mtext>5d</mtext><mo>&#8594;</mo><mtext>5&#160;orbital</mtext> </math><br /><br /><math> <mtext>5f</mtext><mo>&#8594;</mo><mtext>7</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>orbital</mtext> </math><br /><br /><math> <mn>5</mn><mtext>g</mtext><mo>&#8594;</mo><mtext>9</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>orbital</mtext> </math><br /><br />In each subshell 1 electron of every orbital will belong to <math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>m</mi> <mi>5</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </mrow> </math> So, Total number of orbitals that will be associate with&nbsp; <math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>m</mi> <mn>5</mn> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </mrow> </math> &nbsp; will be <math> <mrow> <mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32397,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["zero","$\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\pi}$","$\\sqrt{2} \\cdot \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\pi}$","$+\\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\pi}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"For s-electron, $l=0 \\quad \\therefore$ angular momentum $=$ zero","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":32387,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$19.2 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$","$5.76 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$","$1.92 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$","$3.84 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$\n(h $\\left.=6.63 \\times 10^{-34} \\mathrm{Js}\\right)$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{x} . \\Delta \\mathrm{V} \\geq \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{4 \\pi \\mathrm{m}} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{x} \\geq \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{4 \\pi \\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{V}}=\\frac{6.63 \\times 10^{-34}}{4 \\times 3.14 \\times 9.1 \\times 10^{-31} \\times 300 \\times \\frac{0.001}{100}} \\\\\n&=\\frac{6.63 \\times 10^{-34}}{4 \\times 3.14 \\times 9.1 \\times 3 \\times 10^{-31} \\times 10^{-3}} \\\\\n&=0.01933 \\\\\n&=1.93 \\times 10^{-2}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":32331,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#957;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></math></p><p><math><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#981;</mi></math></p><p>Given <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#981;</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8776;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></math></p><p><math><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math> ......(i)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1.5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math> &hellip;&hellip;.(ii)</p><p>Divide (i) and (ii)</p><p><math><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#39;</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2.25</mn><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#39;</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2.25</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#39;</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32385,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$25 \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\pi}$","$1.0 \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\pi}$","$10 \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\pi}$","$2.5 \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\pi}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} \\mathrm{mvr} & =\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi} \\\\ & =\\frac{5 \\mathrm{~h}}{2 \\pi}=2.5 \\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\pi}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":32360,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\left.\\sqrt{\\frac{2 h}{m}\\left(\\lambda_0-\\lambda\\right.}\\right)$","$\\left.\\sqrt{\\frac{2 h c}{m}\\left(\\lambda_{\\mathrm{o}}-\\lambda\\right.}\\right)$","$\\sqrt{\\frac{2 h c}{m}\\left(\\frac{\\lambda_0-\\lambda}{\\lambda \\lambda_0}\\right)}$","$\\sqrt{\\frac{2 h}{m}\\left(\\frac{1}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{o}}}-\\frac{1}{\\lambda}\\right)}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The kinetic energy of the ejected electron is given by the equation\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\nh v &=h v_0+\\frac{1}{2} m v^2 \\quad \\because v=\\frac{c}{\\lambda} \\\\\n& \\text { or } \\quad \\frac{h c}{\\lambda} &=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda_0}+\\frac{1}{2} m v^2 \\\\\n\\frac{1}{2} m v^2 &=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda}-\\frac{h c}{\\lambda_0} \\\\\n&=h c\\left(\\frac{\\lambda_0-\\lambda}{\\lambda \\lambda_0}\\right) \\\\\n\\therefore \\quad & v^2 &=\\frac{2 h c}{m}\\left(\\frac{\\left.\\lambda_0-\\lambda\\right)}{\\lambda \\lambda_0}\\right) \\\\\n& & v &=\\sqrt{\\frac{2 h c}{m}\\left(\\frac{\\lambda_0-\\lambda}{\\lambda \\lambda_0}\\right)}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32218,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cbc13d98-a838-48da-bc1c-d6cdd3961524.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 188px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10e7f6da-74a4-4abc-9139-8255927c7bfb.png\" style=\"width: 195px; height: 189px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/db6e34f5-cda9-4a0d-af15-dacb50d125dd.png\" style=\"width: 187px; height: 184px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/41a9c032-e623-42ea-9005-c4d5dc3e4c10.png\" style=\"width: 182px; height: 191px;\"/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>According to the de-Broglie hypothesis according to which all matters have both particle and wave nature. where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mo>=</mo></math> plank's constant, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>=</mo></math>momentum, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi><mo>=</mo></math> wavelength of particle. This type of graph is called a rectangular hyperbola. As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfrac></math> we will have a rectangular hyperbola.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>λ</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>λ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></math> (constant)</p><p>So, the plot is a rectangular hyperbola.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c6a994fe-4cc9-4185-9ee7-bcbb8892e147.png\" style=\"width: 196px; height: 200px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32208,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lbVHSzfX8SPEjHbXyKgPuO1lzWd_DS6S9QsHR-zP_BM.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WCyKwopaCgt41Bh1QVuvzJq5tCiPAVlPi_cnKHWUbLw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32245,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(A)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mi>Js</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kg</mi></math><br />Debroglie wavelength:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi>mv</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>666</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>666</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math></p><p>(B) The characteristic of electrons emitted is independent of the material of the electrodes of the cathode ray tube. Electrons are fundamental to all traditional forms of matter.</p><p>(C) The cathode rays start from cathode and move towards anode. It was discovered by Sir J.J. Thompson.</p><p>(D) The nature of the emitted electrons is independent on the nature of the gas present in cathode ray tube. They are fundamental particles.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32307,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>hc</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mn>1000</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>663</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kJ</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kJ</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32344,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$4 \\mathrm{~eV}$","$5.5 \\mathrm{~eV}$","$4.5 \\mathrm{~eV}$","$5 \\mathrm{~eV}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\lambda=250 \\mathrm{~nm}=2500 Å$\n$\\mathrm{E}=\\frac{\\mathrm{hc}}{\\lambda}=\\frac{12400}{2500}=4.96 \\mathrm{~eV}$\n$\\mathrm{KE}=$ stopping potential $=0.5 \\mathrm{~eV}$\n$\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{W}_0+\\mathrm{K} . \\mathrm{E}$.\n$4.96=\\mathrm{W}_0+0.5$\n$\\mathrm{~W}_0=4.46 \\approx 4.5 \\mathrm{~eV}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":32400,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$10^{-31}$ metres","$10^{-16}$ metres","$10^{-25}$ metres","$10^{-33}$ metres Planck's constant, $\\mathrm{h}=6.63 \\times 10^{-34} \\mathrm{Js}$."],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\lambda=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\mathrm{mv}}=\\frac{6.6 \\times 10^{-34}}{60 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 10}=10^{-33} \\mathrm{~m}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":32171,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["B and C Only","A and D Only","A and C Only","A and B Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"Checking each statement:<br><b>(A)</b> states $_{12}^{24}Mg$ has 24 protons, but the mass number is 24 and atomic number is 12, so this is INCORRECT.<br><b>(B)</b> Using $\\lambda = \\frac{c}{f} = \\frac{3 \\times 10^8}{4.5 \\times 10^{15}} = 6.67 \\times 10^{-8}$ m, which is CORRECT.<br><b>(C)</b> For $\\lambda_1 = 900$ nm and $\\lambda_2 = 300$ nm, since energy is inversely proportional to wavelength, $E_1:E_2 = 1:3$, not $3:1$ as stated, so this is INCORRECT.<br><b>(D)</b> For photons at $\\lambda = 2000$ pm, energy per photon is $E = \\frac{hc}{\\lambda} = 9.94 \\times 10^{-17}$ J, giving $N = 1.006 \\times 10^{16}$ photons for 1 J, which is CORRECT.<br>The incorrect statements are A and C.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32337,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mn>71</mn></msub><mi>Lu</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>:</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mi>Xe</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>14</mn></msup><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math> (The last electron enters <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> orbital)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32167,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["D","A","C","B"],"answer":3,"solution":"The 2s orbital has one radial nodal surface, which is a spherical surface shown in Figure 1.<br>A nodal surface is where the electron probability density (and wave function) equals zero, meaning $\\psi_{2s}(x) = 0$.<br>From the wave function graph in Figure 2, point B represents where the wave function crosses zero on the x-axis, indicating the location of the radial node.<br>Points A and C show maximum and minimum values respectively, while point D shows a non-zero region beyond the node.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32347,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>36</mn><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>36</mn><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>9</mn><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br />Shortest wavelength for Lyman series&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atom</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;(Lyman series)<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></math><br /><br />SO,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8734;</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#8756;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math><br /><br />longest wavelength for Paschen series of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> atom<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow><mn>36</mn></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>36</mn><mrow><mn>7</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>36</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32308,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4960210e-d104-4d55-b8a8-45c8ac6ebbc6-image.png\" style=\"width: 344px; height: 137px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f848fdb3-ac62-411c-a058-577c426bdb92-image.png\" style=\"width: 344px; height: 130px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a63d2328-aeac-46c8-a2e7-fa2c708b81b4-image.png\" style=\"width: 344px; height: 137px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e1d8282-b716-427e-ada3-ac4198f0a198-image.png\" style=\"width: 344px; height: 131px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Calculate the number of radial nodes using the</p><p>Number of radial nodes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>Radial nodes= number of cuts on x-axis ( r).<br />The curve should start from zero. It can be positive or negative.<br />Size of the curve increases after touching the x- axis every time&nbsp;.</p><p>By keeping all this, we get the following curve:<br />&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/744dce1f-2f78-4ee6-8036-bda308900642-image.png\" style=\"width: 286px; height: 185px;\" /></p><p>Therefor corresponding graph is (C)</p><p>Hence, answer is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32313,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>6</mn><mtext>th&#160;</mtext></msup></math>&nbsp;period <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi>s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>f</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>d</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi>p</mi></math> orbitals are gradually filled.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32175,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$9.835 \\times 10^{12}$","$1.635 \\times 10^{-18}$","$1.635 \\times 10^{-11}$","$9.835 \\times 10^{5}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The energy of an electron in the $n^{th}$ Bohr orbit of a hydrogen atom is given by $E_n = -R_H \\left( \\frac{1}{n^2} \\right)$.<br>The energy required for excitation from $n=1$ to $n=2$ for a single atom is $\\Delta E = E_2 - E_1 = R_H \\left( \\frac{1}{1^2} - \\frac{1}{2^2} \\right) = R_H \\left( 1 - \\frac{1}{4} \\right) = \\frac{3}{4} R_H$.<br>Given $R_H = 2.18 \\times 10^{-11}$ ergs.<br>Converting ergs to Joules: $1 \\text{ erg} = 10^{-7} \\text{ J}$.<br>So, $R_H = 2.18 \\times 10^{-11} \\times 10^{-7} = 2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ J}$.<br>The energy required per atom is $\\Delta E = \\frac{3}{4} \\times 2.18 \\times 10^{-18} = 1.635 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ J}$.<br>To find the energy required per mole of electrons, multiply by Avogadro's number $N_A \\approx 6.022 \\times 10^{23} \\text{ mol}^{-1}$.<br>Energy per mole $= 1.635 \\times 10^{-18} \\times 6.022 \\times 10^{23} \\text{ J mol}^{-1}$.<br>Energy per mole $\\approx 9.846 \\times 10^5 \\text{ J mol}^{-1}$.<br>Comparing with the given options, $9.835 \\times 10^5$ is the closest value.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32354,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"As per <math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>l</mtext></mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math> rule electrons fill first in that orbital which&nbsp;have least <math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>l</mtext></mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math> value.<br />When <math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>l</mtext></mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math> values are same, then electron fills that orbital which have lowest <math> <mtext>n</mtext> </math> value.<br />when <math> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow> </math> as per <math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>l</mtext></mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math> rule when <math> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow> </math><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>ns</mtext></mrow> </math> subshell <math><mo>⇒</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow> </mfenced><mtext>d</mtext></mrow> </math> subshell <math><mo>⇒</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow> </mfenced><mtext>f</mtext></mrow> </math> subshell <math><mo>⇒</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>np</mtext></mrow> </math> subshell <math><mo>⇒</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mn>7</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mn>6</mn></math><br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32152,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\text{Li}^{2+}, 3$","$\\text{He}^+, 3$","$\\text{He}^+, 2$","$\\text{Li}^{2+}, 2$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The radius of the $n$-th Bohr orbit for a hydrogen-like species is given by the formula:<br><br>$r_n = a_0 \\dfrac{n^2}{Z}$<br><br>where $a_0$ is the Bohr radius of the hydrogen atom ($52.9$ pm), $n$ is the principal quantum number, and $Z$ is the atomic number.<br><br>Given $r_n = 70.53$ pm, we can write:<br><br>$70.53 = 52.9 \\times \\dfrac{n^2}{Z}$<br><br>$\\dfrac{n^2}{Z} = \\dfrac{70.53}{52.9} = 1.333 = \\dfrac{4}{3}$<br><br>Checking the given options:<br>For $\\text{Li}^{2+}$ and $n = 3$, $Z = 3 \\Rightarrow \\dfrac{n^2}{Z} = \\dfrac{9}{3} = 3$<br>For $\\text{He}^+$ and $n = 3$, $Z = 2 \\Rightarrow \\dfrac{n^2}{Z} = \\dfrac{9}{2} = 4.5$<br>For $\\text{He}^+$ and $n = 2$, $Z = 2 \\Rightarrow \\dfrac{n^2}{Z} = \\dfrac{4}{2} = 2$<br>For $\\text{Li}^{2+}$ and $n = 2$, $Z = 3 \\Rightarrow \\dfrac{n^2}{Z} = \\dfrac{4}{3}$<br><br>The ratio matches for $\\text{Li}^{2+}$ and $n = 2$.<br><br>Answer: $\\text{Li}^{2+}, 2$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32358,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$10^{-33} \\mathrm{~m}$","$10^{-35} \\mathrm{~m}$","$10^{-31} \\mathrm{~m}$","$10^{-25} \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"De Broglie wavelength $(\\lambda)=\\frac{h}{m v}$\n$$\n\\frac{6.63 \\times 10^{-34}}{6.63 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 100}=10^{-33} \\mathrm{~m}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32311,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["It can be zero for 1s orbital","It can be negative for 2p orbital","It can be zero for 3p orbital","It can never be zero for 2s orbital"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>From the following&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>&#936;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> function graph&nbsp;(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>&#936;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp; probability density)<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>&#936;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> can be zero for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>p</mi></math>&nbsp;orbital other than infinity.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/13365264-aa8f-4201-8e02-64cd3b5fac1a-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 266px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32238,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The magnetic moment of the metal ion can be calculated using</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt><mi>BM</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo></math>number of unpaired electrons.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>BM</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>90</mn><mi>BM</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>BM</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>24</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32327,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> orbital","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> orbital","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> orbital","<math><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi></math> orbital"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>This graph shows one radial node<br />Formula of radial node <math><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> ; angular node <math><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> ; total node <math><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Principal quantum number<br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Azimuthal quantum number</p><p>Radial nodes:</p><p>for <math><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> <math><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br />for <math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br />for&nbsp;<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br />for&nbsp;<math><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32318,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7cf196c2-99fd-4f93-83dd-11f95f53fa7e-image.png\" style=\"width: 277px; height: 135px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>kE</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi>max</mi></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>hC</mi><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>kE</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>300</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>kE</mi></math><br />So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mi>KE</mi></mfenced><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>222</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>21</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32179,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["C and D Only","A and C Only","A, C and D Only","A and B Only"],"answer":1,"solution":"Element with atomic number 9 is Fluorine<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VY7goFNakHZhJSUgB_Mr4p0Cwhnrx7vk0JVKyfknBZ0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32151,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The energy of a photon is given by the relation:<br><br>$E = \\dfrac{hc}{\\lambda}$<br><br>For the two radiations, the energies are $E_1 = \\dfrac{hc}{\\lambda_1}$ and $E_2 = \\dfrac{hc}{\\lambda_2}$.<br><br>The ratio of their energies is:<br><br>$\\dfrac{E_1}{E_2} = \\dfrac{\\lambda_2}{\\lambda_1}$<br><br>Substituting the given values $\\lambda_1 = 2000$ and $\\lambda_2 = 6000$:<br><br>$\\dfrac{E_1}{E_2} = \\dfrac{6000}{2000} = 3$<br><br>Answer: $3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32312,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>8</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>529</mn><mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Li</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></msub></mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></msub></mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>529</mn></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>[</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>]</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub></mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub></mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>529</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>[</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>]</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#916;R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#916;R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null}]